<h3>About PGP Neighbors</h3>
<hr><hr>

<h4>What are PGP and GPG?</h4>
<p>PGP stands for Pretty Good Privacy. Check out <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pretty_Good_Privacy">this article</a>.
GPG stands for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_Privacy_Guard">GNU Privacy Guard</a>. It allows you to generate your key,
    sign keys, view your signature, and more.</p><hr>

<h4>What is the Web of Trust?</h4>
<p>The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_of_trust">Web of Trust</a> is a decentralized model, with the advantage
    that you don't need to trust any central authority to declare a key as being 'trusted.' There are more than 1.3 million
    public keys in the Web of Trust.</p><hr>

<h4>What is PGP Neighbors?</h4>
<p>Those with PGP keys and GPG installed can run <code>gpg --list-keys</code> to view the signatures on their own key, but cannot
    view the signatures on others' keys. PGP Neighbors provides a way to view your nth nearest neighbor in a way that is simple to use.</p><hr>

<h4>What is a 'nearest neighbor?'</h4>
<p>Your 1st 'nearest neighbors' are the group of people who have signed your public key. Your 2nd 'nearest neighbors' are the group of people who have
signed the keys of your 1st 'nearest neighbors,' and so on. Simply put, your nth nearest neighbors are the people who are n degrees of separation
from you in the Web of Trust.</p><hr>


